# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2004-summer-paralympics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1960-summer-paralympics] The **9th Annual International Stoke Mandeville Games**, retroactively designated as the **1960 Summer Paralympics**, were the first international Paralympic Games, following on from the Stoke Mandeville Games of 1948 and 1952.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1960-summer-paralympics] They were organised under the aegis of the International Stoke Mandeville Games Federation.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1960-summer-paralympics] The term "Paralympic Games" was approved by the International Olympic Committee (IOC) first in 1984, while the International Paralympic Committee (IPC) was formed in 1989.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1960-summer-paralympics] The Games were held in Rome, Italy from September 18 to 25, 1960, with the 1960 Summer Olympics.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1960-summer-paralympics] The only disability included in these Paralympics was spinal cord injury.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1960-summer-paralympics] There were 400 athletes from 23 countries.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1960-summer-paralympics] Ludwig Guttmann, the founder of the Stoke Mandeville Games along with Antonio Maglio, head of the Spinal Centre in Rome organised the event which was the first Stoke Mandeville Games to be held outside the UK.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1960-summer-paralympics] The top 10 NPCs by number of gold medals are listed below.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1960-summer-paralympics] The number in parentheses indicates the number of participants from each NPC.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] The **1964 Summer Paralympics** (Japanese: 1964年夏季パラリンピック, Hepburn: *1964-Nen Kaki Pararinpikku*), originally known as the **13th International Stoke Mandeville Games**, were the second Paralympic Games to be held.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] They were held in Tokyo, Japan, and were the last Summer Paralympics to take place in the same city as the Summer Olympics until the 1988 Summer Paralympics.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] The Summer Paralympics, so far the only Paralympics held in Tokyo to take place with Spectators, as the 2020 Summer Paralympics in Tokyo held without spectators due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] In contrast with the 1960 Games, many events had more than three participants, meaning that athletes were no longer guaranteed a medal upon completing their event.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] Tokyo hosted the Summer Paralympic Games again in 2020.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] Nine sports were competed at the 1964 games.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] In athletics, a wheelchair racing event in the form of a 60 m dash was added; previously the athletics program had included only field events.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] Wheelchair racing has since become one of the most prominent Paralympic events.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] The physical medals themselves were created by a team of patients led by engineering instructor George Butler.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] The medals awarded displayed an engraving of a globe on one side paired with an image of the sport awarded on the other.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] Due to the fact that this was the first time the games were called the Paralympics, the words written on the medals said "Stoke Mandeville International Games – Tokyo 1964." The medals were also engraved and coated by George Butler himself.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] Athletes from 17 of the 19 National Paralympic Committees (NPCs) won at least one medal.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] By default, the table is ordered by the number of gold medals the athletes from a nation have won.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] The number of silver medals is taken into consideration next and then the number of bronze medals.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] If nations are still tied, equal ranking is given and they are listed alphabetically by IPC country code.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] With a few exceptions, each event contributed one medal of each type to the table (although for team events, multiple physical medals were actually awarded).
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] Two bronze medals were awarded in the dartchery, snooker and table tennis events.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] Some swimming events did not award silver or bronze medals.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] At the start of the Paralympic Games there was no precision in reporting the results of the competitions.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] However, as can be seen from a 1968 Israeli newspaper reporting an interview with the athlete, she was the same athlete who had won medals in swimming and table tennis in Tokyo 1964.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] Athletes with outstanding performances included Margaret Harriman of Rhodesia who won two gold medals in archery, and Serge Bec of France who won two individuals gold medals, one team gold medal and one team silver medal.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] Dick Thompson of the United Kingdom won two individual golds, one silver and one bronze in athletics.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] The United States' Ron Stein won six golds and South Africa's Daniel Erasmus won two golds and two silvers in athletics.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] Nineteen delegations participated in the Tokyo Paralympics.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] The 1964 Games marked Austria, Fiji, Japan and South Africa's Paralympic Games début.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] South Africa had just been banned from taking part in the 1964 Summer Olympic Games, due to its policy of apartheid.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] It was not, however, banned from the Paralympics until 1980 Summer Paralympics, as Japan (in a host country position) did not oppose its participation.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] A letter from archery medalist Irene Preslipski published in the *Times Leader* on December 1, 1964, also mentions delegations from Ceylon, Mexico and the Philippines marching in the opening ceremony.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] However, these countries only sent in officials.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] The Opening ceremony was organized in the Yoyogi Park, and the Closing Ceremony at Yoyogi National Gymnasium.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] About 5000 spectators were present at both of the ceremonies.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] Then Crown Prince Akihito and Crown Princess Michiko were present in both of them.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] Earlier it was thought that the Games might not get much media coverage, due to the focus on the Olympic Games, but both radio and television media gave high coverage to the Games.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] Most coverage in the media viewed the new Paralympics highly, and considered its new execution very well-done.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] The dedication to those with a variety of disabilities was thought to contribute to overall "international goodwill." This also made the Paralympic organization seem more "humane" since it was thought to be a good way of integrating disabled people into social and work environments.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] British press was notably criticized by the founder of the games, Dr Ludwig Guttmann, for what he considered to be "poor coverage" of the games.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] He felt that in comparison to other countries, British press seemed to view the Paralympics not as a sports event, but as standard news.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] Yoshisuke Kasai was the chairman of the board of directors.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] The board had 3 vice-chairmen, namely T.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] The auditor of the organizing committee was M.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] Tozawa, and the secretary general was K.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1968-summer-paralympics] The **1968 Summer Paralympics** (Hebrew: המשחקים הפאראלימפיים בקיץ 1968) were the third Paralympic Games to be held.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1968-summer-paralympics] Organised under the guidance of the International Stoke Mandeville Games Federation (ISMGF), they were known as the **17th International Stoke Mandeville Games** at the time.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1968-summer-paralympics] The games were originally planned to be held alongside the 1968 Summer Olympics in Mexico City, but in 1966, the Mexican government decided against it due to difficulties.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1968-summer-paralympics] The Israeli government offered to host the games in Tel Aviv, a suggestion that was accepted.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1968-summer-paralympics] The opening ceremony took place in the Hebrew University stadium at the Givat Ram campus in Jerusalem and the games took place in Ramat Gan, Tel Aviv District, at the Israel Sports Center for the Disabled.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1968-summer-paralympics] The closing ceremony took place in the Tel Aviv Trade Center.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1968-summer-paralympics] Therefore, these games were the first in Paralympic history to not be held concurrently with the Olympic Games.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1968-summer-paralympics] Lawn bowls was included in the program for the first time.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1968-summer-paralympics] In wheelchair basketball, a women's team event was added, as was a 100 m wheelchair race for men in athletics.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1968-summer-paralympics] The top ten listed NOCs by number of gold medals are listed below.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1968-summer-paralympics] The host nation, Israel, is highlighted.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1968-summer-paralympics] Twenty-eight delegations took part in the Tel Aviv Paralympics.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1968-summer-paralympics] Canada, Denmark, Ethiopia, India, Jamaica, New Zealand, South Korea and Spain took part in the Summer Paralympics for the first time.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1968-summer-paralympics] Having made its Paralympic Games début four years earlier, South Africa continued to compete at the Paralympics, by sending a delegation to the Tel Aviv Games.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1968-summer-paralympics] It was, at the time, banned from the Olympic Games due to its policy of apartheid, but it was not banned from the Paralympics until 1980 Summer Paralympics in Arnhem.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1972-summer-paralympics] The **1972 Summer Paralympics** (German: *Paralympische Sommerspiele 1972*), the fourth edition of the Paralympic Games, were held in Heidelberg, West Germany, from 2 to 11 August 1972.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1972-summer-paralympics] Organised under the guidance of the International Stoke Mandeville Games Federation (ISMGF), they were known as the **21st International Stoke Mandeville Games** at the time.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1972-summer-paralympics] The games ended 15 days before the 1972 Summer Olympics held in Munich, also in West Germany.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1972-summer-paralympics] As with previous Paralympics, the 1972 games were intended for wheelchair athletes only.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1972-summer-paralympics] However, demonstration events such as goalball and a 100 m sprint for the visually impaired allowed visually impaired competitors to participate for the first time.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1972-summer-paralympics] The host nation, West Germany, is highlighted.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1972-summer-paralympics] Forty-two delegations took part in the Heidelberg Paralympics.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1972-summer-paralympics] Bahamas, Brazil, Czechoslovakia, Egypt, Hong Kong, Hungary, Kenya, Malaysia, Mexico, Peru, Poland, Romania, Uganda and Yugoslavia competed for the first time.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1972-summer-paralympics] Between 1964 and 1976, South Africa was competing at the Paralympics for the third time.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1972-summer-paralympics] Although banned from the Olympic Games due to its policy of apartheid, it was not banned from the Paralympics until 1980, and West Germany, as host country, did not object to its participation.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1972-summer-paralympics] Its invitation to take part in the 1972 Summer Olympics was withdrawn by the International Olympic Committee four days before the opening ceremony, in response to African countries' protests against the Rhodesian government.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1972-summer-paralympics] But as the Paralympics that year were held before the Olympics (and between 1968 and 1984 organised independently ), Rhodesia was able to take part in the 1972 Paralympic Games.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] The **1976 Summer Paralympics** (French: *Jeux paralympiques d'été de 1976*), branded as **Torontolympiad – 1976 Olympiad for the Physically Disabled**, was the fifth Paralympic Games to be held.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] They were hosted by Toronto, Ontario, Canada, from 3 to 11 August 1976, marking the first time a Paralympics was held in the Americas and in Canada.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] The games began two days after the close of the 1976 Summer Olympics in Montreal.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] This was the first time global politics interfered with the Paralympic Games.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] The provincial government at Queen's Park eventually covered the tab.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] Two groups, both with the same President - Ludwig Guttmann - were involved in the decision-making: the International Sports Organisation for the Disabled and the International Stoke Mandeville Games Federation.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] Guttman and Robert Jackson, Chairman of the Organizing Committee, worked to convince the Canadian government to honour their promises of support the teams without money to send their delegations and were largely successful.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] Nevertheless, a small number of African countries withdrew to participate in Paralympics, following on from the 1976 Summer Olympics when 25 countries boycotted the Games, and after this situation, those National Olympic Committees were threatened with exclusion from future events.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] Later, a series of efforts were made to develop a joint policy with the International Olympic Committee.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] Rhodesia was not allowed to participate as the Canadian government refused to grant visas for the Rhodesian Paralympic team to attend the competition.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] The opening of the 1976 games was held at Woodbine Race Track in north Etobicoke.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] There was no athletes' village, so competitors were housed at collegial campus of York University (Keele campus), University of Toronto (St.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] George Campus), and the CNIB national headquarters.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] Israeli athletes were housed in a fourth secret venue due to the specific and undisclosed security concerns, and fear of a terrorist attack.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] Closing ceremonies and the athletics events took place at Centennial Park Stadium.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] Centennial Gymnasium and Centennial Park's Olympic Pool were the venues for the swimming events.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] The 1976 games marked the first time that there was television coverage of Paralympic events.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] Some events were shown live, with daily bulletins shown to viewers in Southern Ontario.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] Within the Toronto area, a small consortium of local cable companies (including Trillium Cable and Rogers Cable) carried the games on channel 10 after CTV and Global TV declined to carry them.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] At the 1976 games, amputees and visually impaired athletes competed for the first time; previous editions of the Paralympic Games had included only wheelchair athletes.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] Within the sport of athletics, new wheelchair racing distances of 200 m, 400 m, 800 m and 1500 m were added.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] Shooting and goalball, both previously demonstration events, were included as official medal sports.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] The host nation, Canada, is highlighted.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] Forty-one delegations took part in the Toronto Paralympics.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] Burma, Colombia, Ecuador, Greece, Guatemala, Indonesia and Luxembourg made their first appearances.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] South Africa was competing at the Paralympics for the fourth time.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] Although banned from the Olympic Games due to its policy of apartheid, it was not banned from the Paralympics until 1980, and Canada, as host country, did not object to its participation.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] These were, however, to be its last Paralympics before the dismantling of apartheid; The Netherlands, as hosts of the 1980 Games, declared South Africa's further participation "undesirable".
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-winter-paralympics] The **1976 Winter Paralympic Games** (Swedish: *Paralympiska vinterspelen 1976*) were the first Winter Paralympics.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-winter-paralympics] They were held in Örnsköldsvik, Sweden, from 21 to 28 February 1976.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-winter-paralympics] The disabilities included in this Paralympics were blindness and amputees.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-winter-paralympics] Sixteen countries took part with 196 athletes.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-winter-paralympics] There were competitions in Alpine and Nordic skiing for amputee and visually impaired athletes, and a demonstration event in ice sledge racing.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-winter-paralympics] They were originally known as the **1st Winter Olympic Games for the Disabled**.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-winter-paralympics] The top 9 NPCs by number of gold medals are listed below.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-winter-paralympics] The host nation (Sweden) is highlighted.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-winter-paralympics] In brackets is the number of athletes per nation.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1976-winter-paralympics] British involvement in these Games was covered in an edition of the Thames Television current affairs series *This Week*.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] The **1980 Summer Paralympics** (Dutch: *Paralympische Zomerspelen 1980*), branded as the **Olympics for the Disabled**, were the sixth Summer Paralympic Games.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] They were held in Arnhem, Netherlands, from 21 to 30 June 1980.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] The Soviet Union, hosts of the 1980 Summer Olympics, were invited to host these Paralympics.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] However, disability sport was not there, and they passed; notoriously, a statement was issued denying the existence of any disabled people in the country (labelled "invalids" by Soviet officials).
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] Soviet Paralympic teams were first represented in the 1988 Summer and Winter Games, also the last while the Soviet Union was extant.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] The first Paralympics on former Soviet territory would be in 2014.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] There was controversy during the preparation for these Games over the inclusion of a team from South Africa.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] In the Netherlands, public and official opinion was against the inclusion of the South African team and pressure came from a number of sports organisations against the Organising Committee.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] The Dutch Parliament was negative as well.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] Eventually, the parliament decided against allowing the participation of the South African team.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] Although "much of the publicity relating to the South African participation had been negative, it did succeed in bringing the disabled sports movement into the minds of many people who would not have otherwise considered the subject at all.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] Dutch organisers also increased visibility through their fundraising ... building a fund that would hold a surplus years after the games.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] The 1980 Paralympics were the first ever to have mascots: a pair of squirrels, Noggi and Joggi, designed by Necky Oprinsen from Sint-Michielsgestel.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] They were chosen through a design competition by Dutch broadcaster AVRO.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] Competitors were divided into four disability categories: amputee, cerebral palsy, visually impaired, and wheelchair.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] It was the first time that cerebral palsy athletes competed in the Paralympics.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] Volleyball was added to the program as a new sport.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] Forty-three delegations took part in the Arnhem Paralympics.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] Iceland, Kuwait and Sudan made their first appearances.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] Prior to the Games, the States General (national Parliament) of the Netherlands, as host country, adopted a motion declaring South Africa's participation "undesirable", due to its policy of apartheid.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] The 1980 Games thus marked South Africa's first absence from the Summer Paralympics since it had joined the movement in 1964, and it remained absent until 1992.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] The Netherlands' decision thus corrected the anomaly whereby South Africa had been banned from the Olympic movement since 1960, while still being authorised to take part in the Paralympic Games.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] The host nation, Netherlands, is highlighted.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] The **2004 Summer Paralympics** (Greek: Θερινοί Παραολυμπιακοί Αγώνες 2004), the 12th Summer Paralympic Games, were a major international multi-sport event for athletes with disabilities governed by the International Paralympic Committee, held in Athens, Greece, from 17 to 28 September 2004.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] 3,749 athletes (2,600 Men and 1,149 Women) from 135 countries participated.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] During these games 304 World Records were broken with 448 Paralympic Games Records being broken across 19 different sports.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] 8,863 volunteers worked along the Organizing Committee.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] Four new events were introduced to the Paralympics in Athens; 5-a-side football for the blind, quads wheelchair tennis, and women's competitions in judo and sitting volleyball.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] Following a scandal at the 2000 Summer Paralympics, in which the Spanish intellectually-disabled basketball team was stripped of their gold medal after it was found that multiple players had not met the eligibility requirements, ID-class events were suspended.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] It was also the last time that the old Paralympic symbol was used.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] The new Paralympic symbol was introduced in 2006.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] Athens was chosen as the host city during the 106th IOC Session held in Lausanne, Switzerland on 5 September 1997.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] The Greek capital had lost its bid to organize the 1996 Summer Olympics to the American city of Atlanta nearly seven years before, during the 96th IOC Session in Tokyo, Japan on 18 September 1990.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] Under the direction of Gianna Angelopoulos-Daskalaki, Athens pursued another bid, this time for the right to host the Summer Olympics in 2004.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] Unlike the 1996 bid committee that was seen arrogant when the city was bidding, the 2004 bid was lauded for its low scale, humility, honest and earnestness, its focused message, and a more real e a detailed bid concept.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] Unlike, nine years before where concerns and criticisms are raised during the unsuccessful 1996 bid – primarily when was talked in critical subjects about the city's infrastructural readiness, its air pollution, its budget and politicization of the Games events and their preparations.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] Another factor that contributed to the Greek capital's selection was a growing sentiment among some IOC members to restore some original values of the Olympics to the Modern Games, a component which they felt was lost during the 1996 Summer Olympics.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] This was the last edition of the Summer Paralympics in which cities could make the decision whether or not to host the Games.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] As they were still seen as an optional and second-tier event.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] All the 11 bidding cities agreed to accept these requirements, but only three proposed different organizations.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] The same torch design used for the Olympics was used for the Paralympic Games.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] The flame was lit in a ritual carried out at dusk on September 9, 2004, in the Temple of Hephaestus, at the foot of the Acropolis and resulted in the fire raised from a forge and a reenactment of one of the founding myths of the city of Athens.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] The first torchbearer was the swimmer Kostantinos Fykas who won 2 gold medals in Sydney, 4 years earlier and 1 silver in Atlanta.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] The relay took it throughout Athens metropolitan area, and its route wanted to contrast with that of the Olympic torch, by demonstrating the modern side of Greece, passing through 54 municipalities and covering a distance of 410 km.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] The journey began from the heart of Athens, in Thiseio.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] After the forge ceremony, the Paralympic Torch stopped at Odeon of Herodes Atticus.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] The route also passed by the Temple of Poseidon, Sounion and Brauron, as well as through the cities of Megara and Elefsina, before continuing along the coast towards Sounio and the Marathon Dam.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] On September 17, the Paralympic Flame arrived in the Olympic Stadium during the Opening Ceremony.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] A total of 680 torchbearers took part in the relay.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] A total of 1567 medals were awarded during the Athens games: 519 gold, 516 silver, and 532 bronze.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] China topped the medal count for the first time with more gold medals, more silver medals, and more medals overall than any other nation.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] In the table below, the ranking sorts by the number of gold medals earned by a nation (in this context a nation is an entity represented by a National Paralympic Committee).
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] Among the top individual medal winners was Mayumi Narita of Japan, who took seven golds and one bronze medal in swimming, setting six world records in the process and bringing her overall Paralympic gold medal total to fifteen.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] Chantal Petitclerc of Canada won five golds and set three world records in wheelchair racing, while Swedish shooter Jonas Jacobsson took four gold medals.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] France's Béatrice Hess won her nineteenth and twentieth Paralympic gold medals in swimming.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] Swimmer Trischa Zorn of the United States won just one medal, a bronze, but it was her 55th ever Paralympic medal.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] She retained her position as the most successful Paralympian of all times.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] The opening ceremony for the 2004 Summer Paralympics took place on the evening of 17 September 2004 in the Athens Olympic Stadium.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] The formal part of the ceremony began with the Hymn to Liberty sung by the Games ambassador, the Greek singer Vicky Leandros.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] Using an allegory with theatrical parts as well as light and music, the show featured the story of human achievement and perseverance in the face of adversity, always falling back to the motif of human achievement and the strength of life being a considerable force in the world.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] Afterwards, the Parade of Nations started and was accompanied by the music of French composers Yves Stepping and Jean Christophe.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] The music featured throughout this parade told the story of Hephaestos, a Greek god and son of Zeus and Hera.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] Being unusually small, he was cast from Mount Olympus and left to die by his mother, but was nursed back to health by Thetis and Eurynome, who also taught him how to work a foundry.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] Despite all adversities and the impairments he incurred as a result of being cast down, Hephaestos grew up to become the god of Fire and Metallurgy, tying his myth into the topic of overcoming adversity through perseverance and the strength of life.After that, fireworks erupted at the stadium.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] There were 150 local support staff involved and 400 volunteers.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] The children were from ages 8 to 17, coming from Australia, France, Spain, Greece and Germany.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] The actors Afroditi Simiti, Giannis Zouganelis and the interpreter Sophia Roboli were the Masters of Ceremonies.At the end of the ceremony, Greek tenor Mario Frangoulis performed alongside Kalli Georgelli a special song composed to the event.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] During the speeches, Sir Philip Craven, the President of the International Paralympic Committee, was accompanied by the head of the organizing committee Gianna Angelopoulos-Daskalaki, who told the athletes and the audience: "The Olympic flame illuminates athletes.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] Many of you will leave Athens with medals, but all of you will leave as champions." Phil Craven quoted Democritus in his speech: "Two thousand years ago, Democritus said "To win oneself is the first and best of all victories." This holds true for all athletes, but especially for Paralympians.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] The paralympic flame was lit by Georgios Toptsis, a pioneer athlete in Greece.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] Toptsis was won three medals (one silver and two bronze) between the 1988 and 1996 Games.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] The closing ceremony for the 2004 Summer Paralympics took place on 28 September 2004.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] The traditional cultural display was removed from the ceremony as a mark of respect for the deaths of seven teenagers from Farkadona, travelling to Athens, whose bus collided with a truck near the town of Kamena Vourla.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] has decided to cancel the closing ceremony of the 12th Athens Paralympics as initially planned and scheduled because of the tragic accident that cost the life of pupils.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] Flags were flown at half mast and a minute's silence was observed.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] In contrast with the formal nature of the opening ceremony, the athletes entered the stadium for the final time as a collective.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] This was followed by official matters, including the handover to Beijing, hosts of the 2008 Summer Paralympics, and a cultural presentation by the delegation (which included a presentation of the new Paralympic "agitos" emblem).
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] A procession of young people then made their way to join the athletes in the centre of the stadium carrying paper lanterns, before the Paralympic flame was extinguished.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] In the following calendar for the 2004 Summer Paralympics, each blue box represents an event competition.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] The yellow boxes represent days during which medal-awarding finals for a sport were held.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] The number in each yellow box represents the number of finals that were contested on that day.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] The dots inside each box indicate that there was competition that day.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] Although the Paralympic Games were broadcast to around 1.6 billion viewers throughout 49 countries, some controversy was caused when no American television network stayed to broadcast the event.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] This resulted in some US viewers having to wait almost 2 months until the coverage was broadcast, compared with live feeds in several other countries.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] During the IPC General Assembly held in December 2001, the IPC decided to remove events for the intellectually disabled and make several changes to other classifications of different events.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] A new team event was also added in the program: 5-a-side football for the blind.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] In total, 43 fewer events were played than in Sydney.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] However, with 16 being played for the first time and five being replaced.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] As a result, 32 fewer finals were held than Sydney, totaling 519 finals.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] Facilities of the 2004 Summer Paralympics in the Greater Athens area.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] In total 15 venues were used at the 2004 Summer Olympics.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] Unlike the Olympic Games, the swimming events were held in the Athens Olympic Aquatic Centre indoor pool.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] Athletes from 135 National Paralympic Committees competed in the Athens 2004 Paralympics.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] 12 National Paralympic Committees made their dèbut at the Paralympic Games: Bangladesh, Botswana, Cape Verde, Central African Republic, Ghana, Guinea, Nepal, Nicaragua, Niger, Suriname, Tajikistan and Uzbekistan competed for the first time.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] Five National Paralympic Committees that sent delegations to Sydney 2000 did not send delegation to Athens for various reasons and they were: Laos, Madagascar, Mali, Papua New Guinea, and Vanuatu.
[src:2004-summer-paralympics/2004-summer-paralympics] In Athens there was also no group of independent or neutral athletes.
